==English==

===Etymology===

* Old English '''hweogol''', '''hweol'''
* [[Proto-Indo-European]] '''*[[qwel]]''' ''going around'' 

Akin to:

* Dutch '''wiel''' ''wheel''
* Old Norse '''hvél''' and  '''hjól''' ''wheel'' 
* Greek '''kyklos'''   ''circle, wheel'', '''polos'''   ''axle''
* Latin '''colere''' ''to cultivate, inhabit'' = ''turn around''
* Sanskrit '''carati''' ''he moves, wanders'', '''cakra''' ''wheel''
* Old Korean '''huaet-gwi-et-gol''' (햇귀엣골), literally meaning, ''sun-rise ring''; or possibly '''huae-ui-gol''' (해의골) ''sun's ring, sun's halo''

NB : the Korean etymology is false and pure hazard. Korean is not connected to indoeuropean languages.

